### Stack and Queue in C#

Stack and Queue are specialized collections for LIFO (Last-In-First-Out) and FIFO (First-In-First-Out) scenarios.

### Stack<T>

A stack is a LIFO collection. The last element added is the first one removed.

```csharp
Stack<string> stack = new Stack<string>();
stack.Push("First");
stack.Push("Second");
stack.Push("Third");

string top = stack.Peek();  // "Third" (without removing)
string item = stack.Pop();  // "Third" (removes and returns)
```

### Stack Methods

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `Push(T)` | Add element to top |
| `Pop()` | Remove and return top element |
| `Peek()` | Return top element without removing |
| `Contains(T)` | Check if element exists |
| `Clear()` | Remove all elements |
| `Count` | Number of elements |
| `ToArray()` | Copy to array |

### Stack Use Cases

```csharp
// Undo/Redo operations
var undoStack = new Stack<string>();
undoStack.Push("Change 1");
undoStack.Push("Change 2");
string lastChange = undoStack.Pop();  // "Change 2"

// Expression evaluation
// Backtracking algorithms
// Call stack simulation
```

### Queue<T>

A queue is a FIFO collection. The first element added is the first one removed.

```csharp
Queue<string> queue = new Queue<string>();
queue.Enqueue("First");
queue.Enqueue("Second");
queue.Enqueue("Third");

string next = queue.Peek();    // "First" (without removing)
string served = queue.Dequeue();  // "First" (removes and returns)
```

### Queue Methods

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `Enqueue(T)` | Add element to end |
| `Dequeue()` | Remove and return front element |
| `Peek()` | Return front element without removing |
| `Contains(T)` | Check if element exists |
| `Clear()` | Remove all elements |
| `Count` | Number of elements |
| `ToArray()` | Copy to array |

### Queue Use Cases

```csharp
// Print job scheduling
var printQueue = new Queue<string>();
printQueue.Enqueue("Doc1.pdf");
printQueue.Enqueue("Doc2.pdf");
string nextJob = printQueue.Dequeue();

// Request processing
// Task scheduling
// Breadth-first search
```

### Stack vs Queue

| Aspect | Stack | Queue |
|--------|-------|-------|
| Order | LIFO | FIFO |
| Add | Push (top) | Enqueue (back) |
| Remove | Pop (top) | Dequeue (front) |
| Peek | Top element | Front element |
| Use case | Undo, backtracking | Queuing, scheduling |

### Priority Queue (C# 10+)

```csharp
// Elements with priority
PriorityQueue<string, int> pq = new();
pq.Enqueue("Low", 3);
pq.Enqueue("High", 1);
pq.Enqueue("Medium", 2);

string next = pq.Dequeue();  // "High" (highest priority)
```

> **Key Point:** Use Stack<T> for LIFO scenarios (undo, backtracking). Use Queue<T> for FIFO scenarios (job scheduling, request processing). Both provide O(1) push/enqueue and pop/dequeue operations. For priority-based queuing, use PriorityQueue<TElement, TPriority>.

### Concurrent Versions

```csharp
ConcurrentStack<T>    // Thread-safe stack
ConcurrentQueue<T>    // Thread-safe queue
```

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Stack - LIFO
        var browserHistory = new Stack<string>();
        browserHistory.Push("Home");
        browserHistory.Push("About");
        browserHistory.Push("Contact");

        Console.WriteLine("Back button:");
        while (browserHistory.Count > 0)
            Console.WriteLine($"- {browserHistory.Pop()}");

        // Queue - FIFO
        var ticketQueue = new Queue<string>();
        ticketQueue.Enqueue("Ticket #1");
        ticketQueue.Enqueue("Ticket #2");
        ticketQueue.Enqueue("Ticket #3");

        Console.WriteLine("\nProcessing tickets:");
        while (ticketQueue.Count > 0)
            Console.WriteLine($"- {ticketQueue.Dequeue()}");
    }
}
